EvilBox-One

Target IP: 192.168.194.212

Scanning



There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

Performing a directory search leads to some interesting directories. The /robots.txt contains the text Hello H4x0r; maybe this is a username? The /secret/ directory is interesting.

Performing a directory search on /secret/ is the next step.


The interesting page is the /evil.php. This page is blank and the source-code is not displayed to us. However, when I performed LFI fuzzing on this page, I found an interesting parameter called command. Maybe the target machine is vulnerable to LFI attacks?


And bingo. The target machine is vulnerable to LFI and directory traversal attacks. From the screenshot above, we get an interesting user called mowree. Time to look for any interesting log files. After trying to find log files to poison, I had no luck. I also looked for any config files with credentials but I had no luck.



Then I went back to mowree and try to find the SSH key of this user, and it worked! I used curl to get the key in a nice format. Looks like this key is encrypted, so we need to decrypt it.


After copying the encrypted key and storing it inside a file called ssh_key, I used john to obtain the hash of this key. Then I used john to crack the password of this encrypted key! I obtained the password unicorn.

Exploitation


I changed the permission of the ssh_key to 400, and logged in as the user mowree using this key. Now I have a foothold on the machine as mowree.

Privilege Escalation


After transferring LinPeas to the target machine, I found an interesting section stating I have write permissions over the /etc/passwd file. If this is the case, then I can create a new root user and switched to that user to gain root privileges.


And now I have a root shell. I created the password rooted using the command openssl passwd rooted and obtained the hash jP4Xfdn/sYf4Q. Then I used the command echo 'super:jP4Xfdn/sYf4Q:0:0:root:/root:/usr/bin/bash' >> /etc/passwd to append the new user and password. And finally, I switched to the new user to gain a root shell.

Flags
